18:["$","p","1",{"children":"This version which you see in the image above -- is the most commonly seen and used equation to explain bitcoin’s issuance schedule. This equation is often sited as the reason why Bitcoin has a 21Million issuance cap, which is Bitcoin’s main value proposition."}]
19:["$","p","2",{"children":"$undefined"}]
1a:["$","p","3",{"children":"But did you know, that this equation is:"}]
1b:["$","p","4",{"children":"A) not in the white paper."}]
1c:["$","p","5",{"children":"B) not exactly how it is implemented in the code."}]
1d:["$","p","6",{"children":"$undefined"}]
1e:["$","p","7",{"children":"When I started to dig into it to better understand it myself, I came across these two realizations, and was surprised by them.."}]
1f:["$","p","8",{"children":"$undefined"}]
20:["$","h2","9",{"children":"In the White Paper"}]
21:["$","p","10",{"children":"I recently went back and read through the Bitcoin white paper. I was surprised to see that this supply issuance equation does not appear anywhere in it. In fact, there is no mention of the 21Million supply cap either. In fact, there is very little math or code referenced in the white paper. But here’s why: The only math included was a probability equation that Satoshi included to demonstrate how difficult it would be for an attacker to “double-spend” or cheat the system – and how that probability decreases quickly. The White Paper is a high-level discussion / announcement of the Bitcoin Network as a System. It doesn’t include any implementation details. So this issuance equation is never mentioned in the white paper, but instead was actually derived from the code itself. And yet, it is not exactly how it is implemented in the code, either."}]
22:["$","p","11",{"children":"$undefined"}]
23:["$","h2","12",{"children":"The Math"}]
24:["$","p","13",{"children":["If we analyze this equation, we see that it is what is known as a geometric series. The ",["$","span","1",{"className":"katex","children":[["$","span","0",{"className":"katex-mathml","children":["$","math",null,{"xmlns":"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML","children":["$","semantics",null,{"children":[["$","mrow","0",{"children":["$","mo",null,{"children":"∑"}]}],["$","annotation","1",{"encoding":"application/x-tex","children":"\\sum"}]]}]}]}],["$","span","1",{"className":"katex-html","aria-hidden":"true","children":["$","span",null,{"className":"base","children":[["$","span","0",{"className":"strut","style":{"height":"1em","verticalAlign":"-0.25em"},"children":"$undefined"}],["$","span","1",{"className":"mop op-symbol small-op","style":{"position":"relative","top":"0em"},"children":"∑"}]]}]}]]}]," symbol is shorthand for representing a series, or a loop. The series starts with the number set at the bottom (zero) - and goes up until the number at the top (32). We've all heard that Bitcoin has a 21 million supply cap, and if you actually calculate this equation, you'll see that it does produce the sum of 21 million."]}]
25:["$","p","14",{"children":["Each term is ",["$","strong","1",{"children":"half the previous one"}]," (50, 25, 12.5, 6.25...). This halving series, when summed to infinity, converges to exactly ",["$","strong","3",{"children":"2× the first term"}]," — a classic property of geometric series with ratio ½. The 210,000 × 50 = 10.5M, doubled = ",["$","strong","5",{"children":"21M"}],".",["$","br","7",{"children":"$undefined"}],["$","br","8",{"children":"$undefined"}],"But you may have heard that the",["$","strong","10",{"children":" true supply"}]," is actually a little bit less than 21 million. In fact it is 2,099,999,997,690,000 sats. So this left me with the question: Why is this slightly less than 21M?",["$","br","12",{"children":"$undefined"}]]}]
26:["$","p","15",{"children":"This equation we are all so familiar with is reverse engineered from the code. But it is actually a little bit of a simplification of the way the bitcoin supply is issued because it shows 50 BTC, but a more accurate representative equation would show this calculation in SATS. (5,000,000,000 / 2^n)."}]
27:["$","p","16",{"children":["$","span",null,{"className":"katex-display","children":["$","span",null,{"className":"katex","children":[["$","span","0",{"className":"katex-mathml","children":["$","math",null,{"xmlns":"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML","display":"block","children":["$","semantics",null,{"children":[["$","mrow","0",{"children":[["$","munderover","0",{"children":[["$","mo","0",{"children":"∑"}],["$","mrow","1",{"children":[["$","mi","0",{"children":"i"}],["$","mo","1",{"children":"="}],["$","mn","2",{"children":"0"}]]}],["$","mn","2",{"children":"32"}]]}],["$","mn","1",{"children":"210000"}],["$","mo","2",{"children":"⋅"}],["$","mrow","3",{"children":[["$","mo","0",{"fence":"true","children":"("}],["$","mfrac","1",{"children":[["$","mn","0",{"children":"5000000000"}],["$","msup","1",{"children":[["$","mn","0",{"children":"2"}],["$","mi","1",{"children":"i"}]]}]]}],["$","mo","2",{"fence":"true","children":")"}]]}]]}],["$","annotation","1",{"encoding":"application/x-tex","children":"\\sum_{i=0}^{32} 210000 \\cdot \\left(\\frac{5000000000}{2^i}\\right)"}]]}]}]}],["$","span","1",{"className":"katex-html","aria-hidden":"true","children":[["$","span","0",{"className":"base","children":[["$","span","0",{"className":"strut","style":{"height":"3.0788em","verticalAlign":"-1.2777em"},"children":"$undefined"}],["$","span","1",{"className":"mop op-limits","children":["$","span",null,{"className":"vlist-t vlist-t2","children":[["$","span","0",{"className":"vlist-r","children":[["$","span","0",{"className":"vlist","style":{"height":"1.8011em"},"children":[["$","span","0",{"style":{"top":"-1.8723em","marginLeft":"0em"},"children":[["$","span","0",{"className":"pstrut","style":{"height":"3.05em"},"children":"$undefined"}],["$","span","1",{"className":"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight","children":["$","span",null,{"className":"mord mtight","children":[["$","span","0",{"className":"mord mathnormal mtight","children":"i"}],["$","span","1",{"className":"mrel mtight","chil